Rating: 4
Definitely a keeper and exactly what I was looking for. I have avoided salsa verde for several years after having (and made) many that were way too tart or didn't taste fresh. I recently found a local restaurant that served a great verde which inspired me to try one more time. I rolled up some pulled pork (saved without any bbq sauce and made with a rub that included chili and cumin)in some tortillas, poured a bit of this over, topped with cheese and served with tomato, onion, sour cream, avocado and more sauce on the side. Mmm mmm good!

Rating: 4
I've been making this for years now, with two variations: we leave out the cilantro which everyone in my family finds utterly and absolutely disgusting and we use fresh Anchos (poblanos)instead of the Anaheims. It is still wonderful - delicious on so many things. As others have said - please don't skip the bit of cream. It smooths things out and adds silkiness and great depth of flavor. A touch of salt doesn't hurt either to meld flavors. Enjoy.

Rating: 3
I used a different salsa verde recipe from epicurious - the roasted salsa verde so I can't comment on this one. The roasted is very good. The Ancho Chili Sauce is strange. It looks like my cream almost curdled, although absolutely nothing was even warm when I pulled it together - it is not a smooth, creamy sauce at all and the taste, as others have noted, is not all that great. I'd love to see a picture of what that sauce is suppose to look like. There is lots of spice in this recipe so make sure you and your guests like hot!

Rating: 4
I used Hatch chiles, skipped the serranos and tomatillos altogether, and instead of whipping cream I topped with sour cream. So flavorful and delicious and HOT!

Rating: 4
I used to order the Salsa Verde at our favorite Mexican restaurant when we lived in SC for years. Then I got the bright idea to make it myself. This is as good or better than how I remember theirs. We have trouble getting serrano and Anaheims so I have to substitute with either the little red Thai or Birds Eye, whatever I can find. It's still excellent!

Rating: 4
This is delicious. I'm one of those people for whom cilantro tastes like dishwashing liquid, so I left that out. The only other change I made was to use poblanos instead of anaheims - and 4 instead of 2. I also put in a bit more cream to smooth it out. Everything else is as written - and wonderful. I can't get enough.

