Rating: 4
This salsa verde recipe is excellent!!! The flavor is outstanding. I could use a little more heat. And if you feel the same way, keep more of the pepper's inside membranes in the salsa. That will make it hotter, not the seeds as commonly thought.

Rating: 4
Although this recipe is fairly straightforward, it does require a bit of prep, and takes me about 1 1/2 hours to complete. It's a great thing to make on a lazy Sunday. I did make a few modifications the 2nd time making this. Instead of whipping cream, I used half-and-half, and I used about 2tbsp at that. I also used 2 medium-large poblano peppers and 2 medium jalapenos. I chared them under a broiler, removed the skin and seeded them. I increased the cilantro to about 1/2 cup and even put a little parsley in to thicken up the consistancy a bit. This is a great salsa to put on chicken or pork.

Rating: 4
This is an easy and delicious recipe! I substitued sour cream for the heavy cream, and stewed chicken breast in it, then served it with corn tortillas and Spanish rice. Undoubtedly, this is a new favorite of my family.

Rating: 4
I made this recipe exactly as stated and it was a hit! Very tasty and perfectly spiced for my group. I wouldn't change a thing and I'll certainly make it again. I served it as a salsa topping over pork tamales. I barely had a cup left when dinner was done. Yummy.

Rating: 4
We loved this recipe and it's very easy to make if you have the ingredients on hand. I did not really like it over eggs, but we are eager to try it with chicken enchiladas or possibly with pork. I did not add the cream (lactose intolerant) and did use the lime juice. No serrano chiles were available, so I used a very large jalepeno and retained part of the ribs and seeds to give it a level of heat similar to a seeded serrano. Make this recipe - you won't be sorry if you like salsa at all.

